projectDesc.p: ParlaMint is a project that aims to (1) create a multilingual set of comparable corpora of parliamentary proceedings uniformly encoded according to the ParlaMint encoding guidelines; (2) add linguistic annotations to the corpora and machine-translate them to English; (3) make the corpora available for download and through analysis tools; and (4) build use cases in Political Sciences and Digital Humanities based on the corpus data.

application.label: Tokenisation and sentence segmentation
application.desc: We used a revised version of the LX-tokenizer which splits punctuation marks from words and detects sentence boundaries (Branco and Silva, 2003). We used an adapted version of the tokenizer to prevent the expansion of contractions of prepositions followed by determiners (Généreux et al., 2012).http://lxcenter.di.fc.ul.pt/tools/en/LXTokenizerEN.html

application.label: Lemmatization and UD morphological features and NER marking (PER, LOC, ORG, MISC)
application.desc: For POS-tagging we used the MBT tagger (Daelemans et al., 1996) trained over the CINTIL corpus (Barreto et al., 2006). We adapted the tagset to be conformant to the UD POS tags used in ParlaMint. The CINTIL corpus includes NER annotation. We lemmatized the corpus with MBLEM (van den Bosch and Daelemans, 1999), that combines a dictionary lookup with a machine learning algorithm to produce lemmas. As basis for the dictionary we used a list of wordform - POS-tag combinations mapped to lemmas. This list was produced in-house. The dictionary used in MBLEM contains 102,196 word forms combined with 27,860 lemmas, leading to 120,768 wordform-lemma combinations.https://github.com/LanguageMachines/mbt

application.label: UD syntactic annotations
application.desc: We used the LX-UD dependency parser, adapted to the set of POS and relation types used in ParlaMint.https://portulanclarin.net/workbench/lx-udparser
